[Claim 1]
A power conversion device comprising: a power converter that converts direct current power to alternating current power, wherein the AC side of a single-phase inverter is configured in multiple series connections, and multiple such single-phase inverters collectively supply either direct or alternating current power to loads by summing their output voltages; and a control unit for controlling the power converter, characterized in that:
the single-phase inverter outputting the minimum absolute value of output voltage is designated as the minimal single-phase inverter;
the absolute value of the total output voltage, which is discretely adjustable by selectively combining the outputs of multiple single-phase inverters, is referred to as a gradation level;
the predetermined gradation level where the same total output voltage level is achieved through multiple combinations of output voltages is designated as a special level;
the adjustable gradation levels include at least one such special level; and
the control unit:
controls the single-phase inverters to output the set voltage value total output voltage by selecting combinations of output voltages among the multiple single-phase inverters; and
when changing the gradation level to include the special level in either the forward or backward direction, selects an output voltage combination such that at least one single-phase inverter other than the minimal single-phase inverter maintains its output voltage unchanged.
